{"id":"2207.02880","submitter":"Benjamin Allen","authors":"Benjamin Allen and Alex McAvoy","title":"The coalescent with arbitrary spatial and genetic structure","comments":"67 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"q-bio.PE math.PR","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  The coalescent is a stochastic process representing ancestral lineages in a\npopulation undergoing neutral genetic drift. We introduce an abstract\nformulation of the coalescent that applies to a broad class of neutral drift\nmodels, allowing for arbitrary spatial structure and mating patterns. In this\nformulation, the coalescent is a random sequence of mappings $\\mathcal{C} =\n\\left(C_t\\right)_{t=0}^\\infty$ from a finite set $G$ to itself, representing\nthe ancestry of alleles at a single genetic locus. Here, $G$ represents the\n``sites'' (in individuals, at particular spatial locations) at which these\nalleles can live. The state $C_t:G \\to G$ maps each site $g \\in G$ to the site\ncontaining $g$'s ancestor, $t$ time steps into the past. $\\mathcal{C}$ is\nobtained by iterated composition of ``parentage mappings\", drawn independently\nfrom a fixed probability distribution. Mutation is incorporated by augmenting\nthe state to include a set of mutated sites. Using this formalism, we define\nand analyze biologically relevant quantities, including coalescence time,\ncoalescence branch length, reproductive value, number of mutations prior to\ncoalescence, and stationary probabilities of identity-by-descent and\nidentity-by-state. The limit of low mutation is analyzed in detail. We\nillustrate this coalescent with applications to well-mixed and graph-structured\npopulations, as well as to a diploid population with arbitrary sex ratio.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 6 Jul 2022 18:00:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-07-08"}
